# ============================================================================
# config/nathan.pii.example — template for the local PII sweep pattern list
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The real patterns live in config/nathan.pii, which is GITIGNORED so the
# public repo does not itself leak the literal names the rules are protecting.
#
# To enable the nathan.pii sweep step in scripts/prepublish-check.sh:
#   cp config/nathan.pii.example config/nathan.pii
#   # edit config/nathan.pii to add real patterns
#
# Format:
#   - One ERE pattern per line
#   - Lines starting with # or blank lines are ignored
#   - Each pattern is grep-matched across the repo (excluding .git/,
#     tests/fixtures/, node_modules/, and .gitleaks.toml itself)
#
# Invocation:
#   bash scripts/prepublish-check.sh
# ============================================================================

# Owner attribution (keep your public author email here, for reference; the
# prepublish sweep allowlists it — this is not an exclusion list for secrets,
# just a collaborator/entity name list).
# EXAMPLE: (?i)owner@example\.com

# Full names (first-last variants come first so they match before first-name
# alone). Use the non-capt<person-i>ng (?i) for case-insensitive.
# EXAMPLE: (?i)example\s?firstname\s+example\s?lastname

# First names — anything you don't want appearing in READMEs, migration
# notes, release notes, commit messages, or any other public artifact.
# EXAMPLE: (?i)\bexample_first_name_1\b
# EXAMPLE: (?i)\bexample_first_name_2\b(?!\s+(t<person-i>ng|kay|watts))

# Private project / client codenames (hyphenated + spaced variants).
# EXAMPLE: (?i)\bexample[-_ ]project[-_ ]name\b

# End of template — copy to config/nathan.pii and edit in place.
